        <?php echo $this->stencil->setHeadline('iOS 8'); ?>
        <p><?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Apple', 'C'); ?> announced <strong>iOS 8</strong> on 2 June 2014 at its annual Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (<?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('WWDC', 'IT'); ?>) event, with release announced for sometime in Fall (Northern Hemisphere) or Spring (Southern Hemisphere) 2014. At their <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPhone', 'ITH'); ?> event on 9 September 2014, Apple announced the full release of iOS 8 for 17 September 2014, while also unveiling the <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPhone 6', 'ITH'); ?> and <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPhone 6 Plus', 'ITH'); ?>. With this release, Apple resumed the cycle of dropping support for older devices, specifically the <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPhone 4', 'ITH'); ?>. Supported devices on this release include the <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPhone 4S', 'ITH'); ?> onwards, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPod Touch', 'ITH'); ?> (5th generation), the <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPad 2', 'ITH'); ?> onwards, and the <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('iPad Mini', 'ITH'); ?> (1st generation) onwards. iOS 8 has limited support on the iPad 2, iPhone 4S, and the iPod Touch (5th generation). The current version of iOS is iOS 8.4. This release added support for the all new Apple Music streaming service.</p>
